# WGSL Kernel Organization
#
# All WGSL shaders live as .wgsl source files under runtime/kernels/,
# organized by functional category. They are embedded into C++ via
# gen_wgsl_shaders.py, which generates wgsl_shaders.h.
#
# Categories:
#
#   attention/     GQA decode/prefill, RoPE, KV cache, causal/bidirectional attention
#   conv/          Conv2D, ConvTranspose2D, ResizeNearest
#   elementwise/   Binary/unary ops, cast, where, scale, equal
#   fused/         SiLU*mul, SwiGLU, GELU*mul, gate+residual, concat2d, split
#   matmul/        f32/f16 matmul, GEMM, fp16_gemm
#   moe/           MoE gate, TopK, GatherElements, ScatterElements, indirect matmul
#   norm/          RMSNorm, LayerNorm, InstanceNorm, GroupNorm, SkipRMSNorm
#   onnx_q4/       ONNX Q4 matmul, GatherBlockQuantized (Q4/Q8)
#   quant_q8/      GGUF Q8_0 matmul (all variants), quantization helpers
#   quant_kq/      K-quant matmul (Q4K, Q5K, Q6K), MXFP4
#   shape/         Transpose, Slice, Expand, Gather, Concat, Softmax, TopK, Argmax
#
# Template kernels:
#   Files containing ${T} markers are dtype-polymorphic templates.
#   gen_wgsl_shaders.py generates two constants per template file:
#     WGSL_<NAME>   : f32-instantiated version (valid WGSL)
#     WGSL_<NAME>_T : raw template for runtime instantiateTemplate()
#
# Metadata:
#   Optional first-line comment for codegen hints:
#     // @meta bindings=6 triton=true registry=custom_name noregistry=true
#   If omitted, bindings are auto-counted from @binding(N) annotations.
#
# To add a new kernel:
#   1. Create <name>.wgsl in the appropriate category directory
#   2. Run: python runtime/gen_wgsl_shaders.py
#   3. Reference WGSL_<NAME> in C++ code (via wgsl_shaders.h)
#
# To regenerate after editing any .wgsl file:
#   python runtime/gen_wgsl_shaders.py
